2022-03-15

I’m using the same dataset from A1, “Differential effect of SARS-CoV-2 spike glycoprotein 1 on human bronchial and alveolar lung mucosa models: Implications on pathogenicity.”, published December 13, 2021. The corresponding publication can be found on GEO and in the references.

This experiment compares the expression response of human alveolar and bronchial cells to SARS-CoV-2 spike protein through RNA sequencing. Figure 1 from the paper shows the experimental design.

Figure 1. Experiment design. Rahman et al, 2021.

Differential gene expression

Recall the design of this experiment. There are 24 samples. A samples are alveolar cells and B samples are bronchial cells. _Sp samples were exposed a SARS-CoV-2 spike protein and _C samples were controls.

Now we can answer the first two questions for this section:

  1. Calculate p-values for each of the genes in your expression set. How many genes were significantly differentially expressed? What thresholds did you use and why?
  2. Multiple hypothesis testing - correct your p-values using a multiple hypothesis correction method. Which method did you use? And Why? How many genes passed correction?

I’ll be using the limma package, since_lmFit_ directly supports accounting for multiple confounders, which we have in this dataset. Following the approach in lecture, using Benjamini-Hochberg correction for multiple hypothesis testing since it is less stringent:

design_model <- model.matrix(~ design$cell_type + design$exposure)
minimal_set <- ExpressionSet(normalized_counts)
fit <- limma::lmFit(minimal_set, design_model)
fit2 <- limma::eBayes(fit, trend=TRUE)
topfit <- limma::topTable(fit2, coef=ncol(design_model), adjust.method="BH", number=nrow(normalized_counts))
# Add the gene symbols
output_hits <- merge(
  data.frame(gene = filtered_symbols, row.names = rownames(normalized_counts)),
  topfit,
  by=0,
  all=TRUE
)
# Sort by unadjusted p-value
output_hits <- output_hits[order(output_hits$P.Value),]

  1. Show the amount of differentially expressed genes using an MA Plot or a Volcano plot. Highlight genes of interest.
limma::plotMA(minimal_set, status=output_hits$P.Value < 0.05, main="Genes with differential expression p-value < 0.05")

  1. Visualize your top hits using a heatmap. Do you conditions cluster together? Explain why or why not.
top_hits <- output_hits$Row.names[output_hits$P.Value < 0.05]
heatmap_matrix_tophits <- t(scale(t(normalized_counts[which(rownames(normalized_counts) %in% top_hits),])))
heatmap_col <- circlize::colorRamp2(c(min(heatmap_matrix_tophits), 0, max(heatmap_matrix_tophits)), c("blue", "white", "red"))
heatmap <- ComplexHeatmap::Heatmap(as.matrix(heatmap_matrix_tophits),
  cluster_rows = TRUE, show_row_dend = TRUE,
  cluster_columns = FALSE,show_column_dend = FALSE,
  col=heatmap_col,show_column_names = TRUE,
  show_row_names = FALSE,show_heatmap_legend = TRUE)
heatmap

The conditions are definitely clustering together. In this heatmap, samples of the same cell type and exposure are adjacent and the boundary between groups is visually discernible.
